snippet.textDisplay: 4:12 could improve this explanation, because 1st you told us that the inflammation prevented O2 from diffusing into the blood stream, so why would being placed on a ventilator help? snippet.textDisplay: I understand lowTV having had double eccu pneumonia, but from a patients point of view the patient also needs to extract phlegm which is extremely hard in a low Tv situation. Anti inflamitaries should help prevent the lungs from swelling, also it may help to actually oxygenate the blood from a secondary source, the co2 build up is a real problem thought as it also puts stress on the heart and causes it to race to try and extract the co2. I think most patients probably die as a result of heart failure due to this. Mine raced to over 210 beats per minute on a number of occasions and the stress was frightening. It may help to find an ancillary source of removing co2 from the blood to help stabilise the patient. Also a very fine mist of colloidal silver and hydrogen peroxide could help to treat the infection within the lungs themselves. I now have C.O.P.D and that has its own set of issues breathing wise, this was all due to a very severe reaction to interferon whilst on immunosuppressants. It’s taken years to get to a level of comfort and I have never been to see a pulmonologist yet, my G.P. Probably thinks having C.O.P.D. Means there is no point as there is no cure for C.O.P.D and it’s terminal. Eight years on and I’m still fighting for every breath I take. It’s one thing having a corona virus and getting over it and getting fit again it’s completely different when your struggle is every day you have left in life. God Bless..🤧🏴󠁧󠁢󠁥󠁮󠁧󠁿❤️

snippet.textDisplay: Five years ago a good friend of mine was hospitalized with ARDS.  She was in the hospital/rehab for 6 weeks, much of it in ICU.    They said if she had gotten to the hospital an hour later she would have died.  She went septic, as well as having ARDS.  But what this vid doesn't mention is that the survivors of ARDS often do not have full recovery.    Many, like my friend, end up on oxygen at home.  Some or many end up with severe anxiety (PTSD, basically), from long stays in ICU. Some are left disabled enough they cannot return to work.
